summaries.title: Balancing Pressure, Pride, and Belonging
summaries.summaryText: Daniel expressed pride in representing his family’s aspirations but also noted ongoing struggles with imposter syndrome. He values belonging through peer groups that normalize his experiences as a first-gen student of color in STEM. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Gender Bias and Collaboration
summaries.summaryText: Priya discussed subtle gender bias in group work but found solidarity in women-in-tech clubs. [Part 2/4]

summaries.title: Navigating Gender Bias in Research Environments
summaries.summaryText: She recounted experiences where her technical contributions were overlooked and strategies she used to assert confidence. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Transition from High School to University-Level Engineering
summaries.summaryText: Luis found the shift from project-based high school learning to theory-heavy coursework challenging but rewarding. [Part 2/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Presented senior capstone project on sustainable urban drainage systems, earning department recognition. [Timeline 4]

Joined the Engineering Learning Community, finding peer mentors and emotional support. [Timeline 1]
Struggled during his first programming course, leading him to seek help from tutoring and peers. [Timeline 1]

themes.title: Mentorship Networks as Retention Mechanisms
themes.description: Mentorship emerges as a consistent strategy for increasing belonging and persistence for students from marginalized groups. Aaliyah’s mentorship program demonstrates how peer-led initiatives can fill institutional gaps. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Sense of Belonging in STEM for Students of Color
themes.description: Maria’s reflections highlight how peer representation and visibility in classrooms significantly influence belonging and persistence for Latina women in engineering. [Extended 2]

themes.description: Seeing Latino professionals at SHPE events reinforced Maria’s sense of purpose and belonging in a field where representation remains limited. [Extended 2]

themes.description: Luis’s story demonstrates resilience through peer and cultural support. [Extended 1]

themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 2]

themes.description: Sarah’s work highlights the growing student-led shift toward wellness advocacy within rigorous majors. [Extended 2]

quotes.quoteText: When I walk into a classroom and see no one who looks like me, I remind myself that my presence opens the door for someone else. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Aaliyah reflecting on the impact of representation and visibility.

quotes.quoteText: I realized I had access to engineering summer camps that most of my friends never even heard of — that’s when privilege clicked for me. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Ethan reflecting on his exposure to early STEM opportunities.

quotes.quoteText: Mentorship is how we survive here — sharing what we’ve learned keeps us going when the system doesn’t always see us. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Aaliyah on the value of mentorship networks.

quotes.quoteText: My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Priya describing family expectations.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I look around my class and I’m the only Latina — it makes me question whether I belong here. [Context 1]
quotes.context: Maria reflecting on classroom representation and belonging.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: Having mentors who also came from immigrant families helped me feel like my story belonged here too. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel describing peer mentorship as a belonging intervention.

quotes.quoteText: It took me a year to realize struggling is normal — not a sign that I’m not supposed to be here. [Context 3]
quotes.context: Daniel describing the turning point after joining peer mentoring programs.

quotes.quoteText: Sometimes I feel like everyone else just gets it — like I’m pretending to belong in these classes. [Context 4]
quotes.context: Daniel discussing his sense of imposter syndrome in engineering coursework.

quotes.quoteText: You can’t innovate if you’re burned out — STEM needs to start treating wellness as part of success. [Context 2]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 3]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Visibility of First-Gen Student Resources
areasForImprovement.description: Current communication about financial aid, academic advising, and mentorship resources does not adequately reach first-generation students. Improving targeted outreach through orientation and department emails could reduce inequities in access to support. [Extended 1]
actionItems: Add first-gen resource links to department portals

areasForImprovement.title: Normalize Academic Struggle Through Faculty Messaging
areasForImprovement.description: Faculty can help counter imposter syndrome by sharing personal learning experiences, highlighting that mastery develops over time and through mistakes. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Encourage faculty to include ‘learning journeys’ in course introductions
Develop short workshops on inclusive teaching practices

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Cultural Representation in Engineering Programs
areasForImprovement.description: Students emphasized the importance of seeing role models and mentors from similar cultural backgrounds. Faculty partnerships with student cultural organizations could foster inclusion and belonging. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Integrate cultural competence into departmental events

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 2]
actionItems: Create opt-in mentoring tracks for first-gen students
Provide mentor training focused on inclusive communication
